itou-Charentes, France":"Exoudun, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, France","Bolebrook, Sussex, England":"Bolebrook, Sussex, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hastings","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from Hastings (Sussex), near which the English army was defeated by the Normans in 1066. The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Hǣsta</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>. In the latter part of the 12th century, at the time of William the Lion, the surname was taken to Scotland, where it assimilated instances of the native Scottish surname <b>Harestane</b>.","English: variant of   Hasting   with Middle English genitival <i>-s</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hOistín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Oistín</i>’, the Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Augustine</i> (see   Austin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hasting","meanings":["English: from the Norman personal name <i>Hastang</i>, <i>Hastenc</i>, <i>Hasten</i> (Old Norse <i>Hásteinn</i> ‘high’ + ‘stone’). See also   Hastings  ."]},{"name":"Heston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Heston (Middlesex) or Histon (Cambridgeshire). The Middlesex placename derives from Old English <i>hǣs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, while the Cambridgeshire placename may derive from Old English <i>hyse</i> ‘shoot, tendril’, also ‘son, youth’, + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish (Mayo): variant of   Hastings  ."]}]},{"name":"Delcia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of the Late Latin name <i>Delicius</i>, a derivative of <i>deliciae</i> ‘delight’. Use as a given name seems to be a modern phenomenon; it is not found in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Delysia","meanings":["Feminine form of the Late Latin name <i>Delicius</i>, a derivative of <i>deliciae</i> ‘delight’. Use as a given name seems to be a modern phenomenon; it is not found in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":50,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":59,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Delcia Hastings was born about 1165, in Little Easton, Essex, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Hastings, was 39 and her mother, Delcia Estains, was 66. She had at least 2 daughters with Henry de Cornhill, Sheriff of London. She died on 15 May 1245, at the age of 81, and was buried in Exoudun, Deux-Sèvres, Poitou-Charentes, France."},"et":{"Abt 1165–15 MAY 1245":"umbes 1165–15. mai 1245","1165–1245":"1165–1245","1135–1194":"1135–1194","1183–1249":"1183–1249","1112–1240":"1112–1240","1180–1224":"1180–1224","1195–1252":"1195–1252","1127–Male":"1127–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","December 1224":"detsember 1224","15 MAY 1245":"15. mai 1245","1165":"1165","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","1183":"1183","1180":"1180","1249":"1249","1215":"1215","1127":"1127","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1245":"1245","1112":"1112","Abt 1165":"umbes 1165","1100":"1100","Lusignan, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Lusignan, Vienne, Poitou-Charentes, Prantsusmaa","Little Easton,Essex,England":"Little Easton, Essex, Inglis